<DOC><DOCNO> AP890506-0050 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0646EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-06 0654</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0673</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Follow Tornadoes; Record Cold In Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Severe thunderstorms today followed killer tornadoes overportions of the Carolinas, dumping more than an inch of rain in anhour, and flood watches were posted in the middle and northernAtlantic coastal states.   More than two dozen tornadoes touched down Friday evening in theCarolinas. The hardest-hit area appeared to be in SpartanburgCounty, S.C., where a tornado killed at least three people andinjured more than 30.   In all, the storm was blamed for the deaths of at least 16people since Thursday night. Four people died in North Carolina;three in South Carolina; one in Louisiana; seven in Texas; and onein Oklahoma.   Thunderstorms produced baseball-sized hail and 60 mph winds inLexington County, S.C., where numerous trees and power lines werereported down.   Trailers were overturned in Farmington, N.C., and trees fellonto mobile homes in Summerfield and Rockingham counties.   A severe thunderstorm struck Baltimore, uprooting trees withwind gusts to 78 mph.   Richmond, Va., received more than an inch of rain in one hourearly this morning, while some central Virginia and westernMaryland towns reported up to 5 inches of rain from the storm.   Parts of eastern Pennsylvania received 2 to 4 inches of rain. Upto 2 inches fell in the Washington, D.C., area in the six hoursending at 2 a.m. EDT.   Rain and scattered thunderstorms spread northeast into nearlyall of New York and New England by early this morning. With theground saturated from recent rainfall, flooding was possible inportions of the middle and northern Atlantic coastal states, fromVirginia to southern Maine.   Light snow fell across much of Minnesota, Wisconsin and northernMichigan early today.   Unseasonable cold settled into the upper Mississippi Valley andthe northern and central Plains, setting records Friday for thedate in Minneapolis, with 26 degrees, and Rochester, Minn., also 26.   The high for the nation Saturday was 107 degrees in Laughlin,Nev., Bullhead City, Ariz., and Buckeye, Ariz.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from NorthCarolina across the mid-Atlantic states to southern New England;scattered showers and thunderstorms extending from Florida acrosssoutheast Georgia to eastern South Carolina; rain across Maine andNew Hampshire; scattered rain from the lower Great Lakes to theOhio and Tennessee valleys; rain and snow showers scattered overthe upper Great Lakes; and sunny skies from the Plains to thePlateau.   Highs were to be in the 40s from eastern sections of Minnesotaand Iowa to much of the Great Lakes, with readings in the upper 30sover Upper Michigan; in the 50s and 60s from the northern andmiddle Atlantic coast states across the Ohio, Tennessee and middleMississippi valleys to the northern and central Plains; in the 90sfrom the interior valleys of California across southern sections ofArizona and New Mexico to far west Texas; and from 100 to 110 overthe desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs mostly were to be in the 70sand 80s.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 20degrees in Duluth, Minn., to 87 degrees in Phoenix and Glendale,Ariz.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 62 fair; Boston 50 rain; Buffalo 51 showers;Charleston, S.C., 68 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 42 fair; Cleveland48 fair; Detroit 42 partly cloudy; Miami 76 fair; New York 58 rain;Philadelphia 64 showers; Pittsburgh 50 drizzle; Portland, Maine, 47rain; Washington 58 rain.   _Central: Bismarck 29 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 62 fair; Denver 47fair; Des Moines 32 fair; Indianapolis 45 partly cloudy; KansasCity 38 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 26 windy; Nashville 50 foggy;New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis 46 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 63 fair; Anchorage 37 cloudy; Las Vegas 80partly cloudy; Los Angeles 63 hazy; Phoenix 87 cloudy; Salt LakeCity 56 fair; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 61 cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 50 rain; Toronto 46 cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>